  "summary": "Gwendolyn questions Colonel Erskine regarding the disappearance of her stepmother, Helen. Erskine reveals that he and Helen shared a serious romantic connection after meeting on a ship to India, but they agreed to part ways because he was married to Jenny and had children. Years later, while vacationing at the Royal Clarence Hotel in Deal, Erskine encountered Helen again.\n\nGwendolyn notes that Helen's sudden departure from Dillworth one summer night led many to believe she had eloped with Erskine. Erskine denies this, stating his final encounter with Helen occurred on a beach around nine o'clock the evening before he and his wife departed. During that walk, Helen told him to leave immediately. Erskine speculates that Helen ran away to avoid him because she realized he still loved her. When Gwendolyn asks if Helen was afraid of her husband, Erskine recalls that while Helen's husband appeared cheerful, Helen herself seemed worried. He suggests that jealousy can be a terrifying, hidden force.\n\nThe conversation is interrupted by the arrival of Mrs. Erskine, which causes Erskine's demeanor to become rigid and tense. Gwendolyn informs Mrs. Erskine that she found a ring dropped by Mrs. Reed in the garden. As Gwendolyn departs, Colonel Erskine walks her to her car while Mrs. Erskine calls out to Richard regarding an important telephone call.",
